HYPERTENSION - DIAGNOSIS AND MANAGEMENT

Classification:
Normal blood pressure is systolic below 120 mmHg and diastolic below 80 mmHg. Elevated blood pressure is systolic 120-129 and diastolic below 80. Stage 1 hypertension is 130-139/80-89 mmHg. Stage 2 hypertension is 140/90 mmHg or greater. Hypertensive crisis includes urgency (above 180/120 without organ damage) and emergency (above 180/120 with acute organ damage).

Diagnosis:
Diagnosis requires confirmation with two or more readings on two or more occasions. Use standardized measurement technique with patient seated quietly for 5 minutes, feet flat on floor, back supported. Out-of-office measurements including home blood pressure monitoring and ambulatory monitoring are recommended to confirm diagnosis and exclude white coat hypertension.

Lifestyle Modifications:
Weight loss in overweight patients can reduce systolic BP by 5-20 mmHg per 10kg lost. DASH diet reduces systolic BP by 8-14 mmHg. Sodium restriction below 2.4g/day reduces systolic by 2-8 mmHg. Regular aerobic exercise 30 minutes most days reduces systolic by 4-9 mmHg. Limiting alcohol to 2 drinks/day for men, 1 for women reduces systolic by 2-4 mmHg. Smoking cessation reduces cardiovascular risk.

Pharmacologic Treatment:
First-line agents include thiazide diuretics, calcium channel blockers, ACE inhibitors, and ARBs. Thiazide diuretics are preferred for most patients. ACE inhibitors or ARBs are preferred for patients with diabetes or chronic kidney disease. Calcium channel blockers are effective in elderly and African American patients. Beta-blockers are preferred for patients with coronary artery disease or heart failure.

Hypertensive Emergency:
Hypertensive emergency requires immediate IV treatment to reduce BP by no more than 25% in the first hour, then to 160/100-110 within the next 2-6 hours. Agents include IV labetalol, nicardipine, clevidipine, and sodium nitroprusside. Target organ damage includes hypertensive encephalopathy, intracranial hemorrhage, acute MI, acute LV failure, aortic dissection, and acute kidney injury.

Blood Pressure Monitoring:
Home BP monitoring is recommended with validated devices. Measure twice in the morning before medication and twice in the evening for 7 days. Discard first day readings and average remaining. Ambulatory BP monitoring over 24 hours provides the most comprehensive assessment and best predicts cardiovascular outcomes.

Resistant Hypertension:
Resistant hypertension is defined as BP above goal despite use of 3 antihypertensive agents of different classes including a diuretic at maximum tolerated doses. Evaluate for secondary causes including primary aldosteronism, renal artery stenosis, obstructive sleep apnea, and drug interactions. Spironolactone is effective as a fourth agent in resistant hypertension.